# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: university-of-calabria
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Abbot Oliba is considered a key figure in the repopulation of Catalonia based on Roman and Christian culture, and political pacifism and his assemblies of Peace and Truce of God laid the groundwork for one of the first parliaments in Europe.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the Centro de Estudios Universitarios CEU educational group.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It belongs to the Catholic Association of Propagandists, an institution created in 1908 by the Jesuit priest Ángel Ayala.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The main campus of the UAO CEU is the Bellesguard Campus, in the district of Sarrià-Sant Gervasi.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The origin of the current university is in the CDES Abat Oliba, an institution created by Fundación San Pablo-CEU in 1973 in Barcelona.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The center started its activities in January 1974 through an affiliation agreement with the University of Barcelona.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1995 it became known as the Center for Higher Education Abat Oliba and offered degrees in Law, Business Administration and Management, and Economy.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2003, the Parliament of Catalonia recognized Abat Oliba CEU University as a new university.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1992 he acquired the complex built by the modernist architect Bernardí Martorell at the behest of the benefactor Francesca Balart, to convert it into its current headquarters, which opened in 1995.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] That same year, coinciding with the refurbishment by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou, it was renamed the Abat Oliba Higher Education Centre, incorporating university studies in Law, Business Administration and Management and the first cycle of Economics.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Eight years later, in 2003, the Abat Oliba CEU University is recognised by Law 20/2003, of 4 July 2003, of the Parliament of Catalonia.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It thus becomes one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the CEU educational group.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The spring of 2007 saw the birth of the Goliad UAO CEU Awards, prizes given annually by the advertising and communication students of the Abat Oliba CEU University.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2012 the institution started an annual conferenced titled UAO CEU International Journalism Week, lasting an entire week (Monday to Friday), and hosting presentations by professionals and scholars of Journalism.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Also in 2012, the Abat Oliba CEU University and the totality of the Catalan universities pledged to defend the Catalan linguistic immersion model and proposed a coordinated access to the Catalan university system.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The university's rectors since then have been: Juan Corona Ramón (2003–2004) José María Alsina Roca (2004–2009); Carlos Pérez del Valle (2009–2017), Eva Perea (2017-2018), Rafael Rodriguez-Ponga y Salamanca (2019-2024) and Arcadi Gual Sala (since 2024).
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] They offer undergraduate, master's and postgraduate degrees in the areas of Communication, Law and Political Science, Education, Business and Economics, Humanities and Psychology.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017 Unesco awarded the UAO CEU the Chair of Peace, Solidarity and Intercultural Dialogue, to promote a comprehensive concept of peace.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2020 saw the creation of the Antonio de Montserrat Chair of Global Studies and the Jean Monnet Chair on Fiscal Integration in the European Union, financed with European competitive funds from the Erasmus+ call for Jean Monnet activities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] There is also the Labour Observatory, dedicated to current issues in the world of work, and the Institute of Health Sciences.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2020, the university joined the European Federation of Catholic Universities and the International Platform for Cooperation and Migration.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group and is one of three CEU Universities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In addition to its research and teaching function, UAO CEU organises cultural and informative activities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2007 saw the creation of the annual GoliADs UAO CEU Awards for advertising and communication, awarded by students of Abat Oliba CEU University in Barcelona to advertising agencies and the media.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Since 2013, it has organised the BCN Thinking Challenge, a university marathon of social entrepreneurship created by the university's Entrepreneurship Club.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2015, the Education Talks were created, spaces for innovation in education which are organised in two annual sessions, one session on educational innovation and another on a monographic theme.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017, the Digital Communication Week was launched.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Two editions have been held: one focused on the role of artificial intelligence and the other on digital transformation.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is held as part of the Official Master’s Degree in Digital Communication and New Technologies.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Other conferences that the UAO CEU organises are the Law and Society Conference and the European Conference of Christian Anthropology and Mental Health Sciences, which were held for the first time in September 2018 and 2019, respectively.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The UAO CEU was the first university to join the ‘Universitats amb cor’ programme of Caritas Internationalis in Barcelona.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group, the private educational institution that allocates most resources in Spain to scholarships and study grants.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the 2009 Spanish universities ranking by the Institute for Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid, the Abat Oliba CEU University ranks 1st among the Catalan private universities in terms of teaching.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In research, the university holds the 3rd position nationwide.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] One of the patrons of the university is the Archbishop of Barcelona, currently Juan José Omella.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU is the highest-ranking private Catalan university in Spain, as accredited by the Institute of Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In Spain, UAO CEU ranks third place, behind only the University of Navarra and the Comillas Pontifical University.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the study Via Universitària (2016), by the Jaume Bofill Foundation and the Xarxa Vives d'Universitats 85% of UAO CEU students are satisfied with their studies.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The seventh ranking of universities of the CyD Foundation (2020) highlighted the performance of UAO CEU in the fields of international mobility, international teaching staff, placements in companies in the region, graduation rate and rate of return on degree.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the QS World University Rankings, drawn up by Times Higher Education, CEU universities are among the 500 best in the world and rank sixth among Spanish universities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU has its main campus at the Bellesguard Campus, located around the former summer palace of the House of Barcelona, where King Martin of Aragon, also known as Martin the Humane, died.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1900, part of the plot was segregated so that the architect Antoni Gaudí could build a residence for the industrialist Jaume Figueres, known as Torre Bellesguard.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] On the rest of the land, in 1925, the Oblates of the Most Holy Redeemer promoted a religious community for carrying out social work, built by the architect Bernardí Martorell thanks to the generosity of Francesca Balart.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Martorell, a disciple of Gaudí, designed a church with hyperboloid vaults, which today serves as the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The church and the cloister were fitted out as headquarters for the UAO CEU by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou in 1992.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2018, refurbishment work was undertaken in the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra, with the installation of an underfloor heating system and new audiovisual equipment.
[src:university-of-calabria/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2019, the new radio, television and photography studios were inaugurated.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The **Abdelmalek Essaâdi University** is a Moroccan public university established in 1989 and headquartered in Tétouan.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is one of the main higher education institutions in northern Morocco.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university comprises 15 institutions, including faculties, schools, and institutes, distributed across the Tanger-Tétouan-Al Hoceïma region as well as in the city of Larache.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It offers programs in several fields, including sciences, law, economics and management, humanities and social sciences, as well as science and technology.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In 2016, the university inaugurated a Confucius Institute dedicated to the teaching of Chinese language and culture, becoming the third institute of this type in Morocco.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university was ranked 82nd in the 2016 regional ranking of Arab universities published by U.S.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University was founded by virtue of Dahir no.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] 177-398 of 16 October 1975 relating to the creation of universities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition to the Presidency, the UAE currently has 15 institutions, namely: six schools and nine faculties.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition, 2 schools and 6 faculties will soon be opened..
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university includes the following faculties and schools.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The National Schools and the faculty of science and technology deliver a state engineering degree (Diplôme d'Ingénieur d'État).
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The other faculties deliver either a bachelor's (licence) or a master's degree.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university's initial and continuing education programs are aimed at all audiences and offer accredited training in many areas.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university prepares training offers according to the Bachelor framework for accreditation and start of application from the start of the 2021–2022 academic year.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The UAE has been able to develop interesting and promising research potential.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Research at UAE is now structured within 5 CEDs, 38 laboratories, 20 groups and 52 research teams accredited by the University Council (CU).
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] For its part, research and international cooperation have been defined in the university's development strategy as priorities.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is the guarantor of training and research with an international dimension allowing the university to welcome and train foreign students and to offer its students and staff the opportunity of a departure towards other cultures, with a very present African dimension.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university provides students with a web platform providing resources (PDF courses, videos, etc.) for all branches of study.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Confucius Institute inaugurated in 2016, is the 3rd Confucius Institute in Morocco with the objective of learning the Chinese language.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The result of a partnership between UAE, Jiangxi Normal University of Science and Technology (China), HANBAN and the General Directorate of Confucius Institutes.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Since its inception, 2,308 students have registered for Chinese language and culture courses, including 308 ISITT students.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Career Center was created in 2016 with the aim of offering UAE students training in "Soft-Skills" non-technical skills and facilitating their access to employability after their university studies.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] More than 15,000 students have benefited from its physical services and nearly 200,000 virtual users have registered on the careercenter.ma platform, which has received more than 1,915,000 visits.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The center uses computer-aided design, engineering, manufacturing and materials science technologies to transform a 3D model into a physical object.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The objective is to develop applied research meeting the needs to support regional and national socio-economic development.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] A center created to support all components of the university and instill a spirit of tolerance, multiculturalism, law and duty.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Several associations and clubs active in sport, charity work, art, journalism, innovation and entrepreneurship are present in the various schools and institutions of the university.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] There is also a Student Office in all components of the UAE, which oversees the protection of student rights and the transmission of information to the administrative body.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University has signed agreements with its international counterparts.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is an effective partner of more than 32 universities around the world, and foresees a number of 50 in 2023.
[src:university-of-calabria/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The partnership with the socioeconomic fabric on a multidimensional scale is very present.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Situated on a 72-hectare residential campus in the Middle Atlas Mountains at an elevation of approximately 1,650 meters, the university is about 70 km from the imperial city of Fez.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Al Akhawayn University is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education (NECHE).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Al Akhawayn University was created by King Hassan II, who sought to establish a high-quality institution in Morocco modeled on the American higher education system.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] The university was founded by Royal Decree (*Dahir*) in 1993 and inaugurated by the King on January 16, 1995.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] The Arabic name *al-akhawayn*, meaning "the two brothers," symbolizes the fraternal ties between the Kingdom of Morocco and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, whose respective sovereigns supported the project.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Department of State provided funding to the school in 2020 and 2021 through the Middle East Partnership Initiative.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] In 2021, the department paused funding due to reports of sexual harassment against students and faculty members.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] The university said they were taking measures to address the issues.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] The university fired a professor in 2026 due to allegations of sexual harassment.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Al Akhawayn University offers undergraduate and graduate programs through three schools: School of Business Administration (SBA), School of Science and Engineering (SSE), and School of Humanities and Social Sciences (SHSS).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] All programs are structured around a common core curriculum inspired by the American liberal arts tradition.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] English is the primary language of instruction across all programs.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Students also develop proficiency in French, Arabic, and often a third foreign language.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Al Akhawayn University holds accreditation from the New England Commission of Higher Education (NECHE), a US regional accreditor.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] The university is also recognized by the Moroccan Ministry of Higher Education, Scientific Research and Innovation.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] Al Akhawayn University was ranked 1st in Morocco and 44th in the Arab World by Times Higher Education (2018).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-akhawayn-university] It was featured in Times Higher Education's coverage of the global future of liberal arts education (2025).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-andalus-university-for-medical-sciences] The university specializes in medical sciences, and runs a number of training hospitals around the country.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-andalus-university-for-medical-sciences] Al Andalus University for Medical Sciences is a private higher education institution, exists in the Syrian Arab Republic under the provisions of Presidential Decree No.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-andalus-university-for-medical-sciences] (191) Date 6/5/2005, and linked to the Ministry of Higher Education within the limits provided by Legislative Decree No.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It is one of the highly ranked universities in Palestine.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2023, Al Quds University achieved 5–star rating in Quality Standards.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The university is locally known for its innovation programs in the field of high–tech industry and collaborations.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2017, it was ranked as "most socially responsible university" in the Arab world.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2002, Al–Quds Medical School, the medical branch of the university, received official recognition from governing bodies in the United States and Europe.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The idea to establish "Al Aqsa" university in Jerusalem was proposed in 1931 but remained a concept.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The occupation of West Jerusalem and the Palestinian Diaspora hindered its realization.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In the 1950s, the idea was revived, but Jordan focused on establishing a university in Amman instead.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Israeli occupation of East Jerusalem further delayed the establishment of an Arab university.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In the early 1970s, discussions resumed to establish a Palestinian university, resulting in the transformation of existing institutions into universities in the West Bank.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In the late 1970s, independent colleges were established in Jerusalem and its surroundings.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The College of Daawa and Religious Principles, College of Medical Professions, and College of Science and Technology were founded in 1978 and 1979.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 1982, the College of Hind Al-Husseini for Women and the Center for Islamic Archaeology were established.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 1984, steps were taken to unify these colleges, aiming for recognition by the Union of Arab Universities.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] A coordinating committee was formed, allowing the colleges to maintain their separation.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Faculty of Medicine was founded in 1994.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 1995, all colleges and faculties officially amalgamated, establishing Al-Quds University.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] New centers and colleges were opened or merged, offering a comprehensive range of academic programs.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The university emphasized engagement with society, becoming a distinct entity.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Over the past years, Al Quds University has experienced mounting pressure from the Israeli government, both politically and militarily.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Israeli West Bank barrier built in 2004 have impeded university operations.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Students have been injured and many of the students studying at the university have faced tear gas and some students have been shot.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2013 alone, the Israeli army launched 26 separate attacks on the university campus in Abu Dis, resulting in 1,769 injuries to students and staff.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In the early weeks of 2014, the Israeli army conducted three additional attacks on the Abu Dis campus.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Staff and students frequently face summonses, arrests, and intimidation, both at the Abu Dis campus and the premises in the Old City, which have been raided and occasionally closed on multiple occasions.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Simultaneously, the university has been engaged in legal and political battles to secure its existence.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Since 17 years, it has faced the threat of closure by the Israeli authorities.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Despite being fully accredited and licensed by relevant Palestinian bodies, and internationally recognized, the Israeli authorities in occupied East Jerusalem, insist that the university obtain Israeli accreditation or face closure and arrests of its administration.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] However, Israel has also prevented the university from functioning as a unified entity, forcing it to split into two separate institutions.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Al Quds University's attempts to meet Israeli requirements have been unsuccessful thus far.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2023, Israeli Finance Minister Betzalel Smotrich, planned to freeze funds for the university, which was heavily criticized by Hebrew University director, Mona Kassabri, calling it "discrimination".
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Al–Quds University's main campus is located in town of Abu Dis, which borders Jerusalem and have close proximity to the Temple Mount.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The university campus is spread across an area of 47 acres (190,000 m2).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] On several occasion, exhibitions are organized by the university at its campus premises.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] There is a large botanic garden known as "Andalusian Garden", in backyard of the campus.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] These are Abu Jihad Center, Meet Math Museum and Science Museum.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Abu Jihad Center and Museum was originally established in Ramallah in 1997.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The facility was opened in the university campus in 2007.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It consists of three floors, displaying artworks.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Said Khoury IT Center was inaugurated in 2004, by Palestinian entrepreneur Said Khoury.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Old City campus located in the Old City of Jerusalem, consists of three floors.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It is designed in an Islamic architecture.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Nearby notable landmarks are the Mosque of Omar, the Al-Aqsa Mosque, Building Complex (D*ar al-Immara*) and the Temple Mount (*Haram Al Sharif*).
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2015, Al Quds University inaugurated the first Palestinian public university in the Old City of Jerusalem, with funding from the Royal Charity Organization of Bahrain.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The library consists of a collection of books of information and computer technology.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] There is a small girls' campus in Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood of Jerusalem, which is known as the Hind Al–Husseini College for Women.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It was founded by Hind al-Husseini, a Palestinian activist, who rescued orphaned survivors of Deir Yassin massacre, by Zionist militants.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Known as one of the oldest faculty, the Sheikh Jarrah campus provides programs in arts and culture.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It was a mansion of her grandfather Salim al-Husayni, which was later converted into an orphanage, named as "Children's Home in Jerusalem".
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Dar al-Tifl al-Arabi was established as a school, which in 1972, became a college.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The Faculty of Business & Economics is located in another campus, known as "Beit Hanina Campus".
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It is located on the Abdel Hamaid Shoman Street in Jerusalem neighborhood of Beit Hanina.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Beit Hanina campus also serves as an administrative office of the university.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Al Quds Bard College, which was opened in association with the Bard College is the campus of Beit Hanina.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Bayt Mal Al Quds Al–Sharif Agency, a Moroccan organization have planned to construct a new campus of the university in neighborhood of Beit Hanina.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The upcoming campus also includes stadium, green areas equipped with irrigation systems, rainwater recycling station and experimental farm.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It will also include fully–equipped ecological museum and installation of solar panels.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Brandeis University and Al-Quds had a partnership from 1998 to 2013.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The partnership ended in 2013 following a demonstration at Al-Quds in which students in military gear performed a Nazi salute and Brandeis deemed the response from the Al-Quds University administration to be "unacceptable and inflammatory".
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Syracuse University also terminated its partnership in 2013 following the demonstration.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Bard College has dual degree program with Al-Quds University which leads to a bachelor of arts from both institutions.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] It also grants master's degrees in teaching, European studies, and American studies.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The partnership, which was first announced in February 2009, is the first dual degree program between a Palestinian university and an American institution of higher education.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] The college entered into a collaboration with Al-Quds University, which included founding an honors college, a masters program in teaching and a model high school.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] In 2018, Al-Quds University launched the Al-Quds Academy for Global Justice, an institute that will focus on teaching, training, and research in the areas of international criminal law and human rights.
[src:university-of-calabria/al-quds-university] Palestinian Justice Minister Ali Abu Diak also delivered a speech at the event.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Alexandria University is one of the largest universities in Egypt, and the third university established after Cairo University and the American University in Cairo.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Alexandria University has 21 faculties and 3 institutes that teach different types of social, medical, engineering, mathematics and other science.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The university had other branches in Egypt outside Alexandria in Damanhour and Matrouh which later became two independent universities. and Alexandria National University in Smouha area.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Other branches have been set up outside Egypt in Juba, South Sudan, and in N'Djamena, the capital of the Republic of Chad.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The idea to establish a branch of Fouad I University in Alexandria was approved by the university's council on 4 August 1938, with the decision ratified by the Council of Ministers two days later.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The "Zarfoudaki Palace" was leased as the branch's initial location, and studies began on 15 October 1938, with the Faculty of Arts and the Faculty of Law.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The Faculty of Engineering was established in 1941.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] 32 officially established King Farouk I University in Alexandria, which included the faculties of Arts, Law, Medicine, Science, Engineering, Agriculture, and Commerce.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] At the time of its establishment, the university had 1,171 students and 134 faculty members.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The new Faculty of Law was initially housed in a secondary school building.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] In 1942, the Faculty of Agriculture was established in Damanhour.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Following the 1952 revolution, the university's name was officially changed to Alexandria University.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The university continued to expand, adding several new faculties and institutes over the following decades, including the Faculty of Fine Arts in 1957 and the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine in 1975.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] In the 1980s and 1990s, the university added branches and integrated several faculties from Helwan University.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] In the 21st century, the university began to expand internationally, establishing branches in N'Djamena, Chad (2010), and Juba, South Sudan (2014).
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] In 1989, four faculties, located in Alexandria and administered by Helwan University, were annexed to Alexandria University.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] These are the faculties of agriculture, fine arts, physical education for boys and physical education for girls.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Alexandria University was ranked 147th worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2010–2011.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] The 2010 rankings were controversial, as a single professor's practice of publishing a great number of articles in a journal of which he himself was the editor was identified as a crucial contributing factor for the high rating of Alexandria University.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Alexandria University is ranked 1001+ worldwide based on Times Higher Education's World University Rankings 2020.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] Alexandria University is ranked 801-1000+ worldwide based on QS World University Rankings 2021.
[src:university-of-calabria/alexandria-university] It is ranked 701-800 worldwide and 2nd in Egypt based on Shanghai ranking 2020.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR has its origins soon after World War II.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] David Colin, an American journalist in Italy prior to and during the war, settled in Rome.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] While American students and professors visited Rome, Colin helped foster cultural exchanges between Americans and their Italian counterparts.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Over time, informal discussions at his home became more formalized, turning into structured lectures and classes.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] His wife, Joan Carpenter, assisted Colin with this undertaking.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] George Tesoro, an Italian who left Italy in 1940 in protest against Mussolini's fascist regime, began to collaborate with Colin.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] As the program grew, The American University in Rome became reality when AUR was incorporated in 1969 in the District of Columbia with its academic headquarters located in Rome, Italy.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Upon incorporation, Tesoro served as chairman until 1983, when Joseph D.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Ventura, then vice chair, succeeded him.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] During Ventura's time as chairman, the board of trustees became a degree-granting institution from the District of Columbia in 1986.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Margaret Giannini, a professional in the scientific and medical research field, became board chair and served until 2003.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Under her 16 years of leadership, the university grew in its student and faculty numbers, curriculum offerings, and financial and management systems.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Giannini initiated AUR's first accreditation with the Accrediting Council of Independent Colleges and Schools in 1992 and planted the seeds for Middle States accreditation.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] After operating from different locations in central Rome for almost 25 years, AUR moved to its current campus in 1993.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The campus is located on top of the Janiculum, Rome's highest hill, offering views of the city.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Most of its buildings are located on Via Pietro Roselli adjacent to a portion of the Aurelian Wall.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The campus was extended in early 2018 to include an Art Studio, exhibition space and classrooms on via Angelo Masina.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] This building is adjacent to, and shares garden space with, the American Academy in Rome.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The main campus includes two gardens centered around the main A and B buildings, the Evans Hall Library, and the Auriana Auditorium.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The main teaching block (Building B) is part of a Barnabite monastery.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] In 2025, the university announced a major expansion and renewal of its campus.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is governed a board of trustees, president, and a senate.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The highest governing body, the board of trustees, is responsible for overseeing the university and maintaining its academic and financial health and welfare.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Among other duties, the board appoints the president and has final approval of changes to the curriculum proposed by the AUR Senate (the body which, forms and amends academic policies and includes a student government representative).
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The current president of the university is Dr.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Scott Sprenger who assumed the position in July 2020, taking over from Dr.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Richard Hodges OBE, who was named President Emeritus & Professor Emeritus upon completing his tenure.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR is a member of the Association of American International Colleges and Universities and The American International Consortium of Academic Libraries (AMICAL).
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is a liberal arts university with a student-faculty ratio of roughly 16:1.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR's undergraduate student body of roughly 500 students is multicultural and representative of over 30 nationalities.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is regionally accredited by the Middle States Commission on Higher Education, which is an institutional accrediting agency recognized by the U.S.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Secretary of Education and the Council for Higher Education Accreditation.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome is licensed by the Department of Education of the State of Delaware to award associate, bachelor's and master's degrees.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] In Italy, AUR is registered as a legal entity with the Rome Tribunal and it is authorized to operate in Italy by the Ministry of Education, Universities and Research.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR offers three master's degrees (in Peace Studies, Sustainable Cultural Heritage and Food Studies) and eleven bachelor's degree programs with 16 concentrations or tracks, two associate degree programs, and eighteen minors.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Students live off-campus mostly near the university, giving the opportunity to allow the students to immerse in the surrounding communities.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The AUR community of students and faculty publishes a literary journal of student works called Remus each year.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR student run organisations include Student Government and a variety of clubs such as: Veterans Club, Business Club, Communication Club, Culture Club, Italian Studies Club, and International Relations Club which also organises AUR's Harvard National Model United Nations delegation.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The Communication club also supports AUR's Communication Week which is a showcase of the American University of Rome students communications and English work.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The Wolves and She-Wolves are the American University of Rome's soccer clubs which play competitively against Rome's other universities including La Sapienza and Roma Tre University.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Both AUR's men's and women's teams were founding members of their respective intercollegiate tournaments; the men's "Campionato di Calcio delle Università Romane" (2005) and the women's "Campionato Calcio Feminile delle Università Romane" in 2006.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] AUR Wolves, men's soccer team, won the Universities of Rome a5 Football Championship on April 26, 2018, their first trophy since co-founding the league in 2005.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The first mascot in Roman university athletics, Wolfie has been representing AUR since 2006.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] Originally named "Romulus" in reference to the mythical founder of Rome, the name Wolfie was popularized by students and later formally adopted.
[src:university-of-calabria/american-university-of-rome] The American University of Rome hosts a number of study abroad students but also promotes the opportunity for resident students to study abroad from AUR using the AURA program.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The **University of Calabria** (Italian: *Università della Calabria, UNICAL*) is a state-run university in Italy.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] Located in Arcavacata, a hamlet of Rende and a suburb of Cosenza, the university was founded in 1972.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] Among its founders there were Beniamino Andreatta, Giorgio Gagliani, Pietro Bucci and Paolo Sylos Labini.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] It currently has about 35,000 students, 800 teaching and research staff and about 700 administrative staff.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The founders of the university were Beniamino Andreatta, Giorgio Gagliani, Pietro Bucci and Paolo Sylos Labini.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] On 15 January 2009, the main lecture hall was named after Beniamino Andreatta, while the “bridge”, i.e. the main entrance to the cubes, was named after Pietro Bucci.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The University of Calabria, established by Law No.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] 442 of 12 March 1968, had two historical precedents: King Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies, by royal decree issued in 1814 on the initiative of the Province of Cosenza, authorised the Cosenza High School to open a Faculty of Medicine and, to this end, allocated a grant of three thousand ducats.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The first unified government removed this privilege from the Liceo in 1861 (while the schools of Notary and Pharmacy in Catanzaro survived until 1923).
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] It offered courses in medicine, surgery and law.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] Fragale himself personally made his clinical and radiology laboratories available for the chair of Occupational Pathology, which he would have held.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] However, the development of this university was abandoned within a very short time.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The campus covers an area of approximately 200 hectares in the hills of Arcavacata di Rende, a few kilometres from the centre of Cosenza.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] Initially, the university consisted of a single complex, the multi-purpose building in Arcavacata, designed by Massimo Pica Ciamarra, which later became the headquarters of the Department of Pharmacy, Health Sciences and Nutrition.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] As of 2025, new classrooms are under construction (intended for TD medical degree courses).[1] The design of the University of Calabria campus is by Vittorio Gregotti and is part of a phase of his research aimed at combining architecture and landscape planning.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The university complex is shaped like a long pier, approximately two kilometres long, which crosses the Crati river valley.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The pier, called the “Pietro Bucci” bridge, is made of reinforced concrete and includes a vehicle lane and a pedestrian walkway.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The buildings of the various university departments are cubic in shape and up to thirty metres high; they are connected to the horizontal structure of the pier, varying in height according to the changes in the hills of Arcavacata.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The various paths interconnected to the bridge lead to the campus buildings.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] At the base of the university, there is also a residential centre designed by Enzo Zacchiroli, as well as some buildings designed by Vittorio Gregotti himself, while the subsequent residences are the work of Danish architect Tarquini Martensson.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] On 1 August 2024, the Ministry of University and Research accredited the new degree course in Medicine and Surgery TD (Digital Technologies), which will start in Crotone in the academic year 24/25.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The course, strongly supported by the President of the Region, Roberto Occhiuto, is the result of a collaboration between the University of Calabria and the Magna Grecia University of Catanzaro.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] In September, the Ministry also approved the establishment of five medical specialisation schools (Cardiology, Surgery, Haematology, Nephrology and Clinical Pathology) at the “Annunziata” hospital in Cosenza, in synergy with other universities and hospitals in Calabria.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] In January 2025, a meeting was held in the conference room of the Grande Ospedale Metropolitano in Reggio Calabria between MEP Giusy Princi and the rectors of the three Calabrian universities to begin work on setting up a medical course in the city of Reggio.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The Unical reparto corse is a project of The Department of Mechanical Engineering, Management and Energy (DIMEG) that started in 2005.
[src:university-of-calabria/university-of-calabria] The group involves students and professors applying the knowledge gained in their studies to develop race cars that compete in European races.
